We sent out 24 issue alerts between October 1 and June 30, including 11 in January and February. Our average open rate is 33 percent, well above average for advocacy emails. The current system we use for email doesn’t track individual links clicked, so we don’t have that information; however, we are considering moving to a new system that will facilitate that tracking, as well as the possibility of tracking individual emails sent from our alerts.

We held seven workshops over the grant period, including:
--June 2013; job safety training workshop in Gillette, 15 participants;
--June 2013; minimum wage workshop in Riverton, 6 participants;
--September 2013; Spanish-language immigration workshop in Gillette, 35 participants;
--December 2013; Citizen Lobbyist Training in Fort Washakie with tribal council members and top staffers of the Northern Arapaho and Eastern Shoshone tribes, 21 participants.
--January 2014; Citizen Lobbyist Training workshop in Riverton, 19 participants.
--January 2014; Know Your Rights workshop in Rock Springs, 25 participants; 
--February 2014; Citizen Lobbyist Training, including minimum wage and other workshops, in Cheyenne, 39 participants

In April 2014, we held a Workers’ Memorial Day event at the State Capitol in Cheyenne. Over 50 people came together with us to commemorate workers killed and injured on the job and to raise awareness of Wyoming’s dismal job fatality rate and the effect of these tragedies on families and communities. We released our report that day, “Preventable Deaths: Safety and Health in Wyoming.” A copy of that document is available for download at http://equalitystate.org/assets/media/Worker-Safety-2014_web.pdf.
